<br>
Yea well, don't expect anything more than that.  The Court's job is to rule out bad things, not to be the legislative or executive branches =/.  Basically, they are giving schools a chance to keep their goals attuned to race if they want to be, but that they will have to come up with alternate plans.  I'm hoping those plans are also questioned, and until I see what they are, I'm gonna say &quot;shot down&quot; as well.<br>
<br>
I'm the type of person that understands the desire for diversity, however the original goals of affirmative action were not diversity, but to allow non-whites into schools via being given a helping hand.  I definitely do not support that idea.  I DO, however, fully support giving helping hands to those that are economically in need.  I do not use the bias of race when considering economic need.  I never liked affirmative action for that very reason, it still screwed over poor white people who lived in the slums (no matter how few of them there are).  <br>
<br>
My own personal suggestion to fix this was always to collect school funding into one big state-wide fund and to disperse it equally to each public school based on the population of those schools.  THEN, it would be necessary to also change tax laws so that a person cannot write off the amount they pay for private schooling if they were to opt for it.  Some states allow tax options to write off part of your private school funding since your child does not attend public schooling, and thus not *right* for you to have to pay taxes for public schooling.  The reason this is a problem is if one large state-wide equally distributed fund system was created, a large portion of rich families would then withdraw their kids from public schools and go to higher quality private schools.  Now, thats not to say that private schools are higher quality right now, but its to say that they would be created.  Why would they be created?  Because rich people do not want their kids to have the same education as normal people's kids.  They want their kids to have the best, better than the &quot;norm&quot; and would be willing to switch to private schooling if public schools were all equal.  THEN, those same rich families could write off their private schooling costs into state taxes, and thus we haven't really solved any of the problem at all, have we?  By solidifying public school taxes to every citizen of that state (and making it not refundable, written off) you are forcing the rich families to still contribute to public schooling (which they most certainly can afford) and they can still opt for private schooling for their own kids if they so desired...it would just cost them that much more.  They still get the option of being better than the norm, but their precious tax dollars are not lost that are needed to keep decent public schools running.<br>
<br>
The weirdest thing is I never hear of this type of idea in our government.  Perhaps those who run our country are mostly rich people and thus do not want such a program to exist? Who knows.  Perhaps I am not seeing the flaws?  Feel free to express any flaws you might see, because I don't really see it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=radgen>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 775<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/24/03 2:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=747.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Affirmative Action Shot Down</span><hr size=1> Count you misunderstood what I meant.<br>
<br>
The courts are there to put limits on what government can do.  This goal is best served if the legislature and executive know clearly just what the limit is instead of the guessing game we are all playing now with this issue.  It is not legislateing for the courts to draw a line in what can and cannot be done.  It does no good for the courts to go &quot;This crosses the line but we aren't going to tell you where that line is, guess again.&quot;<br>
<br>
The courts have said that race can be used in limited way.  But they need to define just exactly where that limit is instead of what they have been doing.  The rulings have been all over the map. (Part of this reason may be they cannot get a majority to agree to any single definition or specific limit)<br>
<br>
It was pretty obvious that they were going to further limit how race is used, after all the U of M policy DID comply with the last SC ruling so the only reason to take the case was to modify that ruleing.  But they need to clearly tell the other branches of government just where the Constitutional limit is.<br>
<br>
On a side note, I am curious about how the Texas sodomy case will turn out.  In this case the last ruleing upheld laws that regulated sexual practices between consenting adults.  So the only reason i can think of for the court to take this case was because they are thinking of modify THAT ruling and further resricting how government can regulate that area.<br>
<br>
