<br>
While this is a better outcome than an outright acceptance of the points policy, and the clause hoping for the ending of affirmative action is encouraging, the ambiguity of the decision in general will not only ensure the extension of &quot;affirmative action&quot; for at least another generation, but make the entire situation a legal and practical mess as various Universities try out their own various methods of filling their dorms with people who have dark skin rather than light skin. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=largthemiserable>Largthemiserable</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 411<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/24/03 9:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=747.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Affirmative Action Shot Down</span><hr size=1> I can't add much to what has been already said, but the oddest thing that I find with these decisions is this: it is constitutionally sound to allow for race to be used in helping to admit minorites over others in order to diversify a campus, but it's unconstitutional to have any numerical system in place to quantify a person's admission based on race?  So, being a racist is okay, but being a racist accountant is not?<br>
<br>
BTW, I have never been a supporter of things like Affirmative Action and the United Negro College Fund, because these types of institution are no more and no less racist than the views that they are trying to smother (in that all white people think all black people are inferior).  Such institutions do a great job of alienating decent people into not wanting to be equitable, since now a fair-minded person has to be sure to include minorities in their decisions even if the best choice is a white person or a man.  Plus, if I were to start the United Whitey College Fund for low-income white students who were still smart (and mind you, I'm not from an affluent family and was lucky to get a full ride in college based on my brain) I'd be derided as being some racist cracker, even though the possibility is very distinct that my money would actually get to some poor people here and there. <br>
<br>
Even worse, they set a giant hypocrisy right in all male and white faces.  On one hand, you get bombarded every day that all people are equal and that noone should be treated in a special manner.  On the other hand, programs like Affirmative Action flaunt that minorities and women aren't equal and that a government program is needed to level the playing field.  I wouldn't mind one or the other, but both is an ignorant double standard.  If one black leader stood up and said &quot;We're not equal, and that's why we need Affirmative Action&quot;, I'd be more than happy to oblige, as long as claims of equality were shut up.  If a leader of, say, the National Organization for Women, were to stand up and proclaim &quot;We're equal and don't want any program like Affirmative Action&quot;, I'd be delighted, as long as programs like Affirmative Action ceased. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elcheproudfoot>Elche Proudfoot</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mmmmm lobster</span><br>  Posts: 1323<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/24/03 10:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=747.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.woc.org/public/oneirodynia/images/srllogo.GIF height=180 width=180></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Affirmative Action Shot Down</span><hr size=1> My own personal suggestion to fix this was always to collect school funding into one big state-wide fund and to disperse it equally to each public school based on the population of those schools. <br>
